
Configure iptables as a network firewall. You LAN network address is 192.168.25.0/24. Add one more network card to the iptables firewall. This will be your DMZ network. The network address for the DMZ will be 192.168.35.0/24. (Note. Put first network card in bridged mode, second network card in host only mode and third network card in NAT mode for DMZ)
Connect one client  to LAN. Connect second client to DMZ network. Configure iptables firewall such as to allow only DNS traffic, cdac, google and microsoft website for the LAN client. Allow full traffic to the DMZ client.
Install httpd/Apache web server on the DMZ client. Configure port forwarding on the iptables firewall such that the website on the DMZ client is accessible on the WAN IP (Bridged adapter IP address).



  This assignment has **3 machines**:

| Machine               | Network         | Example IP       |
| --------------------- | --------------- | ---------------- |
| Firewall VM           | WAN + LAN + DMZ | WAN: 192.168.1.x |
| LAN Client            | 192.168.25.0/24 | 192.168.25.10    |
| DMZ Client/Web Server | 192.168.35.0/24 | 192.168.35.10    |

---

# Step 1: Configure Firewall Interfaces

## On Firewall VM

Check interfaces:

```bash
ip -br a
```

Assume:

```text
ens160 = WAN
ens224 = LAN
ens256 = DMZ
```

Assign IPs:

```bash
ip addr add 192.168.25.254/24 dev ens224
ip addr add 192.168.35.254/24 dev ens256

ip link set ens224 up
ip link set ens256 up
```

### Verify

```bash
ip -br a
```

Expected:

```text
ens160  192.168.1.x
ens224  192.168.25.254
ens256  192.168.35.254
```

